# THE WITNESS
## Level 2 — Professional Working-Writer Quality

= Synopsis: A detective questions a diner waitress at 3 A.M.
= She's protecting someone she barely knew. He's trying to decide how hard to push.

FADE IN:

INT. SILVER MOON DINER — 3 A.M.

Late-night fluorescent. The kind of diner that becomes its own ecosystem after midnight — regulars who don't talk to each other, a cook who's been listening to the same radio station since 1987.

DETECTIVE VASQUEZ (45, methodical, takes his time) sits at the counter. JUNE PARK (38, has worked this shift for six years, has her own system for reading people) pours coffee she knows he didn't ask for.

VASQUEZ
Busy night.

JUNE
Every night's the same night.

VASQUEZ
The man who ran out. You noticed him?

JUNE
Hard not to. He knocked over the
sugar caddy on his way past.

She picks up a sugar packet from the counter. Sets it down.

JUNE (CONT'D)
Didn't stop to apologize. People
usually apologize.

VASQUEZ
Did you see where he went?

JUNE
Outside. That's all I saw.

VASQUEZ
(patient)
But you'd seen him before.

*June refills his coffee, though it's barely touched.*

JUNE
I see a lot of people.

VASQUEZ
I know. I'm asking about this one.

A long moment. The cook turns down the radio in the back. As if listening.

JUNE
He came in twice a week. Sat at
that stool. Ordered the same thing.
Never caused any trouble.

VASQUEZ
What did he order?

JUNE
(this is not what he asked)
Scrambled eggs and toast. Orange juice.
Tipped well for breakfast food.

VASQUEZ
(softening slightly)
How long?

JUNE
Eight months, maybe. Since the fall.

VASQUEZ
Did he ever talk about himself?

JUNE
(a beat)
He talked about a dog he used to have.
Some kind of shepherd mix. Said it
knew when he was sad before he did.

*She stops. Like she's said more than she meant to.*

VASQUEZ
I'll need you to come in. Formal statement.

JUNE
I understand.

He stands. Puts exact change on the counter plus a few dollars.

VASQUEZ
The eggs any good?

JUNE
Best in the neighborhood. Which isn't
saying much, but I mean it anyway.

He goes. June stands in the late-night quiet. Looks at the stool where the man used to sit.

She wipes the counter. The stool. Everything clean for the next person.

FADE OUT.

= Level 2 craft elements: physical specificity, behavioral subtext,
= dialogue that reveals through indirection, a closing image that resonates.
